  "text": "Mitochondrial separation procedures and buffer solutions were similar to those described by Wibom et al. [CITATION_1] . Samples were homogenized in buffer A (in mM: 100 KCl, 50 Tris, 5 MgCl2, 1.8 ATP, 1 EDTA) and spun at 720 g in an Eppendorf 5417C centrifuge at 4°C. The supernatant was spun at 10,000 g, and the resulting pellet was washed in buffer A, recentrifuged at either 3,000 (liver) or 9,000 g (muscles and heart), and finally suspended in buffer B (in mM: 180 sucrose, 35 KH2PO4, 10 Mg acetate, 5 EDTA) and kept on ice. Aliquots of the suspension were used for measuring mitochondrial ATP production rate, enzyme activities, and protein concentration (DC Protein Assay, Bio-Rad, Hercules, CA).",
